<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="12" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1438,1474,2023]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,326,1661,1687]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
This species is very similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[707,871,1661,1686]" class="Insecta" family="Crambidae" genus="Scoparia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="congestalis">
<emphasis box="[707,871,1661,1686]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">S. congestalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but can be distinguished by the ductus bursae bending in S shape anterior to the colliculum, and the corpus bursae having two signa in the female genitalia. In 
<taxonomicName box="[182,344,1736,1761]" class="Insecta" family="Crambidae" genus="Scoparia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="congestalis">
<emphasis box="[182,344,1736,1761]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">S. congestalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the ductus bursae has a loop before the colliculum, and the corpus bursae has one signum.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
